Regular `enum`:
```typescript
enum Direction { Up = 0, Down = 1 }
const d = Direction.Up;
// Emits: var Direction; Direction[Direction['Up']=0]='Up';Direction[Direction['Down']=1]='Down';
// d becomes: Direction.Up (object lookup)
```

`const enum`:
```typescript
const enum Direction { Up = 0, Down = 1 }
const d = Direction.Up;
// Emits NOTHING for the enum, and d becomes: const d = 0;
// Values are inlined everywhere they're used
```

When to use which:
• `const enum`: better performance (no object), but CANNOT be used with `isolatedModules: true`, Babel, or esbuild — they can't inline across files
• Regular `enum`: safe everywhere, but adds runtime object

Modern recommendation: use `const` objects with `as const` instead of enums:
```typescript
const Direction = { Up: 0, Down: 1 } as const;
type Direction = typeof Direction[keyof typeof Direction];
```

A type-safe builder tracks what has been SET as a type-level phantom:

```typescript
type BuilderState<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };

class QueryBuilder<T extends object, Set extends Partial<Record<keyof T, true>> = {}> {
  private state: Partial<T> = {};

  set<K extends keyof T>(key: K, value: T[K]): QueryBuilder<T, Set & Record<K, true>> {
    this.state[key] = value;
    return this as any;
  }

  build(): Set extends Record<keyof T, true> ? T : 'Error: missing required fields' {
    return this.state as any;
  }
}
```

Simpler alternative — use `satisfies` + object literals:
```typescript
const query = {
  table: 'users',
  where: { id: 1 },
} satisfies Partial<QueryConfig>;
```

The phantom type approach is most powerful when you need to enforce ordering or combinations of chained calls.

TypeScript catches at COMPILE TIME errors that would only appear at runtime in JS:

```typescript
// Access before check — TypeScript warns:
const user: User | null = getUser();
console.log(user.name); // Error: Object is possibly null

// Wrong property name:
const config = { host: 'localhost' };
console.log(config.prot); // Error: Property 'prot' does not exist (typo!)

// Wrong argument types:
function add(a: number, b: number) { return a + b; }
add('hello', 'world'); // Error: string not assignable to number

// Missing required keys:
const user: User = { name: 'Alice' }; // Error: Property 'id' is missing
```

Classes of bugs TypeScript prevents:
• Null pointer exceptions (with strictNullChecks)
• Property access typos
• Incorrect function signatures
• Missing required fields
• Unhandled union cases (with narrowing + exhaustiveness)

What TypeScript CANNOT prevent: runtime data shape mismatches (API responses), logic errors (wrong algorithm), race conditions.
